newsitem.title: GERMANY: Europe feeds buyers seeking Latam sun pellets - ASA.
newsitem.headline: Europe feeds buyers seeking Latam sun pellets - ASA.

text.p: Compound feed producers and traders in northern Europe were actively seeking limited sunseed meal pellets supplies from Latin America, the German office of the American Soybean Association (ASA) noted.
An ASA newsletter said the Rotterdam price of $160 spot fob was up $15 from a month ago in generally firmer markets.
The feed industry still had some gaps in its raw materials cover for the autumn and winter, ASA said.
Pig and poultry feed prices trended higher while dairy cow feed prices remained steady as farmers bought less as they could afford to delayed buying and instead use on-farm feed.
German grain harvest pressure was expected to weigh on feed grain prices and to slightly reduce feeds prices in the very near future, ASA said.
But feed barley prices still exceed last year's by 10 marks and wheat offers are 20 marks above last year's levels as a by-product of high world market prices.
As feeds benefitted from high feedgrain levels, palmkernel expellers for 1996 shipment today cost $130-$133 cif North Germany versus $127-$130 a month ago in the Hamburg market.
Corngluten, a rival in dairy feed uses, rose $5 to $151 for fourth quarter shipment due to lower U.S. corn crop expectations which triggered price rallies.
Active global demand for tapioca boosted spot mark prices fob Rotterdam to 23.25 marks per 100 kilos compared with 22.75 marks in early August.
ASA also said the feed industry needed more rapemeal, where fourth quarter prices fob ex-Hamburg mills of 27.00-27.75 marks consolidated high July levels.
Prices of Peruvian fishmeal for September/October were priced at $540 (64 percent protein), up by $10 from early August, amid lower fish catches and lower stocks at origin.
Chilean fishmeal also rose $10 in August and had a $25 premium over Peruvian material.
